# Supabase security (DNA BJJ)

Follow `docs/02-supabase/rls-and-auth.md` and `.cursor/skills/supabase-backend/`.

## Key usage

| Key | Where | Purpose |
|-----|-------|---------|
| `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` | `src/lib/supabase.js` only | Backend DB access — bypasses RLS |
| `SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` | Frontend repo only (Phase 2) | Coach login via Supabase Auth |

Never expose service role in frontend, logs, or CI output.

## Auth model

- Express validates coach JWT with `supabase.auth.getUser(token)` in `requireAuth`
- Backend uses service role for DB ops — auth gate is Express middleware, not client-side RLS
- RLS is enabled on all tables; anon role can insert waivers only (future public waiver flow)

## Rules

- Never commit API keys — `.env` is gitignored
- Never trust client-supplied IDs without verifying ownership when multi-tenant RLS is added
- After schema changes: run security advisors via Supabase MCP or Dashboard
- Save migration SQL to `supabase/migrations/` when DDL changes (Phase 2)

## Obsolete patterns (do not use)

- Next.js `middleware.ts` session refresh — this is Express, not Next.js
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` env vars — use `VITE_*` in frontend repo
- Lovable client-side Supabase for data writes — all writes go through Express
